{{Infobox person | name = Noël (Noheli) Hitimana | image = File:Noël Hitimana.jpeg | image_size = | caption = | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = in or before 2002<ref name="li 01" /><ref name= "hirondelle 01">{{cite news |title=CONVICTED ITALO-BELGIAN "HATE-RADIO" PRESENTER BEGINS TESTIMONY |author=FH |url=http://www.hirondellenews.org/ictr-rwanda/377-trials-ended/media-trial/18871-en-en-convicted-italo-belgian-qhate-radioq-presenter-begins-testimony79227922 |newspaper=Hirondelle News Agency |date=27 February 2002 |accessdate=22 March 2013}}</ref> | death_place = at a prison in [[Rwanda]] <small>(allegedly)</small><ref name="li 01" /><ref name= "hirondelle 01" /> | occupation = Radio presenter (''animateur''), journalist | spouse = | parents = | children = }} {{wikiquote}} '''Noël''' (Noheli) '''Hitimana''' was a presenter (''animateur'') on the Rwandan radio station [[Radio Télévision Libre des Mille Collines]] (RTLM), which played a significant role in promoting the [[Rwandan Genocide]]. Like the station's [[RTLM#Individuals_associated_with_the_station|other broadcasters]], Hitimana incited violence against [[Tutsi]] on the air.<ref name= "li 01"/>
Prior to his employment at RTLM, Hitimana worked for [[MRND|state-owned]] [[Radio Rwanda]] and the ''Rwanda Bureau of Information and Broadcasting'' from the late 1970s until the early 1990s. During that time, he became popular by routinely greeting the different regions and towns of Rwanda in the early morning, while farmers were waking to work in the fields. This broadcast segment emphasized both the importance of hard work, community and the [[Hutu Power|nationalistic]] views of the ruling [[National Republican Movement for Democracy and Development]] (MRND). Allegedly an [[alcoholic]], Hitimana was fired from Radio Rwanda after insulting [[Rwandan President]] [[Juvénal Habyarimana]] on-air while intoxicated.<ref name= "li 01">{{cite journal |last1=Li |first1=Darryl |last2= |first2= |year=2004 |title=Echoes of violence: Considerations on radio and genocide in Rwanda. |journal=Journal of Genocide Research |volume=6 |issue=1 |pages=25 |publisher= |doi= 10.1080/1462352042000194683|url=https://www.academia.edu/362149/Echoes_of_Violence_Considerations_on_Radio_and_Genocide_In_Rwanda |accessdate=19 March 2013}}</ref>
Due to his popularity throughout the country, Hitimana was one of the first ''animateurs'' hired by RTLM after its founding on 8 April 1993.<ref name= "thompson 01">{{cite book |last=Thompson |first=Allan (Ed.) |authorlink= |title=The Media and the Rwanda Genocide |url=http://www.idrc.ca/EN/Resources/Publications/Pages/IDRCBookDetails.aspx?PublicationID=131 |accessdate=19 March 2013 |year=2007 |publisher=Pluto Press, Fountain Publishers, IDRC |location= |isbn=0-74532-625-0 |page=325 }}</ref> He continued his trademark practice of greeting towns and individuals. Once the Rwandan Genocide began on 8 April 1994, Hitimana modified this habit into naming exact locations and names of alleged [[Rwandan Patriotic Front|RPF]] accomplices, inciting targeted violence and often murder on the named individuals by groups such as the [[Impuzamugambi]] and [[Interahamwe]] militias.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cotton |first1=Cassandra |year=2007 |title='Where Radio is King:' Rwanda's Hate Radio and the Lessons Learned. |journal=Atlantic International Studies Journal |volume= |issue= |pages=4–11 |publisher= |doi= |url=http://atlismta.org/online-journals/0607-journal-gender-environment-and-human-rights/where-radio-is-king/#_ftn43 |accessdate=17 March 2013}}</ref>
Segments by Hitimana made up about 5% of all RTLM broadcasts.<ref name= "thompson 01"/>{{rp|117}}
The studio of RTLM was hit by a bomb on 17 April 1994, with Hitimana being seriously injured. Following the attack, his leg was amputated, resulting in Hitimana leaving RTLM for good.<ref name= "thompson 01" /> Hitimana allegedly died in a Rwandan prison in or before 2002.<ref name="li 01" /><ref name= "hirondelle 01" />
